04407nam a22005775i 9780804783330DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047833307 a10.1515/97808047833302doi  a(DE-B1597)563651  a(OCoLC)1198929519  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aD804.348 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a940.53/18072a940.5318072  aNY 80002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/132373:1 aRothberg, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMultidirectional Memory :bRemembering the Holocaust in the Age of Decolonization /cMichael Rothberg. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Theorizing Multidirectional Memory in a Transnational Age -- t2. At the Limits of Eurocentrism: Hannah Arendt's The Origins of Totalitarianism -- t3. "Un Choc en Retour": Aimé Césaire's Discourses on Colonialism and Genocide -- t4. W. E. B. Du Bois in Warsaw: Holocaust Memory and the Color Line -- t5. Anachronistic Aesthetics: André Schwarz-Bart and Caryl Phillips on the Ruins of Memory -- t6. The Work of Testimony in the Age of Decolonization: Chronicle of a Summer and the Emergence of the Holocaust Survivor -- t7. The Counterpublic Witness: Charlotte Delbo's Les belles lettres -- t8. A Tale of Three Ghettos: Race, Gender, and "Universality" After October 17, 1961 -- t9. Hidden Children: The Ethics of Multigenerational Memory After 1961 -- tEpilogue: Multidirectional Memory in an Age of Occupations -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMultidirectional Memory brings together Holocaust studies and postcolonial studies for the first time. Employing a comparative and interdisciplinary approach, the book makes a twofold argument about Holocaust memory in a global age by situating it in the unexpected context of decolonization. On the one hand, it demonstrates how the Holocaust has enabled the articulation of other histories of victimization at the same time that it has been declared "unique" among human-perpetrated horrors. On the other, it uncovers the more surprising and seldom acknowledged fact that public memory of the Holocaust emerged in part thanks to postwar events that seem at first to have little to do with it. In particular, Multidirectional Memory highlights how ongoing processes of decolonization and movements for civil rights in the Caribbean, Africa, Europe, the United States, and elsewhere unexpectedly galvanized memory of the Holocaust. Rothberg engages with both well-known and non-canonical intellectuals, writers, and filmmakers, including Hannah Arendt, Aimé Césaire, Charlotte Delbo, W.E.B. Du Bois, Marguerite Duras, Michael Haneke, Jean Rouch, and William Gardner Smith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCollective memory in literature. 0aCollective memory. 0aDecolonization in literature. 0aDecolonizationxHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478333040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783330423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804783330.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles